The new ČSSD councillors in the capital will have to overcome, it seems, the obvious language barriers for the members of the Prague Board and the Municipal Council to understand their renewed SDG colleagues.
The Aktuálně.cz period "examined" the members of the new ČSSD Council to check their knowledge of the slang-marked language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current coalition members ruled Prague.
The coded dictionary using the political flower and cream of Prague during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the most well-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been found that the new councilors hardly understand those well-known concepts.
At least, they say that.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"The truth is, I don't know."
"Rather I am a novice in Prague politics," said Councillor of Culture Councilman Lukáš Kaucký during the "collegueo" terminology examination.
And as far as the veteran politician was concerned, Karel Březina reacted the same.
Maybe you know the concept of "golf hole".
"Possibly it's the only expression of all that you asked me that I use from time to time."
"If not, I don't normally use slang."
From the glossary, whose definitions published the newspaper Aktuálně.cz last June before the SDG voting congress, the wording chose six examples, particularly those that are especially related to the municipal authorities of Prague.
The Socialists had to explain the concepts "Voldemort", "greater golf hole in Prague", "go to the pastry shop", "bull's neck", "treason of the capital" and "shine".
Three councilors agreed to undergo the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who will in future be responsible for education in Prague, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councilman, Petr Dolínek, refused directly to do so.
"I don't get into these things or consider how the civic Democrats have fun."
"What I do care about is how we will understand each other in the execution of our programs," he said.
As has been seen, supposedly Councilman Lukáš Kaucký would not have realized that the previous title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former Mayor Bém, Roman Janoušek.
To Kaucký the word "Voldemort" does not say anything to him; the only term he hit in the exam is "the greatest golf hole in Prague".
“It’s about the Blanka tunnel,” says Kaucký, who immediately adds, “But rather I know it from the news.”
"I'm going to have to sign up for a language course," he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also the Councilor for the Environment Lukáš Plachý.
Afterwards, both socio-democrats know who Voldemort really is and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find that character; in addition, he suspects the meaning of "going to the pastry shop".
"I think it means going to a company in Prague"; soon Plachý is revealed that it is the headquarters of the companies of Janoušek.
Like Březina, it indicates that such knowledge obtained from the news, but does not employ such a vocabulary.
According to the participants in the test, among the socio-democrats there is no glossary so familiar to colloquial terms.
"I asked my teammates, but it really seems like we don't have anything like it."
“Rather, between us we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations or we play word games with names,” says the president of the ČSSD Praguense, Petr Hulínský, whose party colleagues call Hulda.
"In school I was called Bříza, but I don't know if my classmates also call me that," confesses his own nickname Karel Březina.
The Aktuálně.cz newspaper tested the name and works.
For his party partners, Weinert is Děda (similar to "yayo") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old"), Representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they associated themselves before the deception elections during the party's patronage, receives the nickname "Igráček" ("playmobil") from some of his companions.
The nicknames are also the only expressions that the socio-democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulínský does not like to be called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuálně.cz discovered even other nicknames for this Prague president.
"The doctor of the rights of the batons" seems to remember that Petr Hulínský obtained his doctorate in Law at the police academy of Bratislava.
The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as it published in a pamphlet
Women considered to be witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually old, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "get" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer only."
“You don’t isolate healthy young women either, because they help in the work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the state of West Africa, Burkina Faso, is engaged in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information leaflet that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a downside.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso can’t read,” the newspaper Die Standard warns of the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Gana, Burkina Faso’s neighboring country, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week, when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to a unfortunate accumulation of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman caught on in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "expel evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The Der Standard newspaper quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: “Human soul eaters always posed a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government tries to appease the witch hunt, in the Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that had allegedly been related to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic."
“To help him, he brought in shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, randomly chosen men and women were forcibly taken among the Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in a report.
On the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand people in detention.
The Bakala tenant: heats up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, elderly and strong, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal tycoon" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried some documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his, his daughter and his son’s, who is serving sentence.
All three have just caught the liberalization of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech kroner a month, the son will pay from next year 4,100 kroner for a two-room apartment with separate second-rate kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," explains half angry, half-resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions “incorrect and indecent,” recommends tenants not to sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, the date on which it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But, in the face of this, man only makes a gesture.
“Everyone says a thing,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a large liberalization testing laboratory.
After New Year it will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rental.
Therefore, Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of the four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to catch number.
"Rent 2011", can be read in a light button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
It hardly gives time or reading "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in the queue.
Shortly after, an elderly marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve usual problems, such as in the past: requests for settlements, insurance issues and similar matters.
Letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava in the tenants’ mailboxes of most of the 44,000 apartments belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them in the cards an increase in rent of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's been working for a week, so it's starting out," the workers who are in it when the client presents himself as a journalist respond, after briefly doubting.
Liberalization and the old mining floors of Bakala are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already treated loud and clear by the vice president of the Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the ČSSD, and now they appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want new soil."
"I didn't even change the damn plate of the bathroom," the man mentioned in the introduction vents.
According to the workers, for the moment they come more than anything retired to check if they receive a discount on rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract by 15 December will also receive half of the February rental discount.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" undoubtedly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about forty or fifty people for rent in 2011," estimates the employee of the window.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rental, an independent judge must resolve the issue.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed possible and completely in accordance with the law," RPG said in a statement.
"No one is going to be judged here," says one of the RPG Byty employees and a man on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
"I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court," he says.
But immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media that they don't sign, so maybe people will wait," he says.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
“Current rentals still don’t even cover the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund,” recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the RPG Byty’s residential portfolio, adding that the sloppy state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for landlords, the main reason for increasing rent.
While during the five years that passed between 2005 and 2010 RPG could with rents invest in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.200 million.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the seats of the waiting room, now repeats some data that stands out in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, that is, more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be at most 7,50 Czech kronor per month per square meter," the screen said.
Only 38% increase in the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 kroner per square meter," says RPG.
At 2,600 apartments, the rental will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalization will not suddenly affect rents, but will scale between four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money of the increase in rent (see the graph) again in the flats, mainly in savings in heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to people who sign the rental increase agreement.
The architects have understood that offices also need childcare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides inside a small nursery with everything like such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio numerous known buildings of Brno came out, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-keddery store.
The company works around 90 people, mainly in the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and draftsmen to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the nursery is one of the benefits offered by Arch.Design to its workers within the framework of its social program.
Builders and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-day-care shop was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-kardery is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (an endowment of more than 2.8 million Czech kroner) they were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When the financing is exhausted (two years), the company Arch.Design has the obligation to keep the mini-kerey running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the financing application contributed to Economy Rating.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified personnel; in addition, a nurse and a teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The nursery currently accommodates children without an age limit, although most of them are under three years of age.
Since it is a "mini-garder", it can only simultaneously accommodate a maximum of five children, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the daycare is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use childcare, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is individual education and care, the contents of the mini-nareship programme are comparable to the regular preschool education programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach to English.
The class has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school kids late when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the companies that sign that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, in short, this program reinforced the marketing of personnel.
The bone house continues to fascinate after 100 years. Look at Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs are reminiscent of a dinosaur's spine and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones."
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought order are observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpent and the twisting of the forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The wavy wood copies the window frames, railings, door ornaments, peepholes and signs.
The Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, emerged from the remodeling of a house of the year 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of making a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, formed by several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project came ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and Gaudí’s Güell Park, in which other pieces of it are located.
Due to its organic form, the locals shortly after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange his inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the construction rules of the moment at all and was not allowed to influence them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently in it the indicated data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so impacted with the result that it asked to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather on the contrary: just fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery of the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connection of space.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the necessary privacy for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the sun’s rays.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and more recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of admission to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí constructions in the city.
