A longer index finger than the annular one indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longest rate than cancelling are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British cancer magazine.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that relative finger length may be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men aged up to 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, particularly if this characteristic is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, according to Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart of more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and simultaneously 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right finger of the right hand shorter than the annular one.
They had the same chance of prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were the same length.
In the case of men with a longer rate than the annular finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men with ages below 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that he does not think that the relationship between finger length and cancer can be "utterly demonstrated".
