The democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America, as well as support for private companies, continues to increase.
Crime raises greater concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it monitors changes in attitudes in the region.
In the results of this year’s survey, conducted in September and early October, two related issues stand out.
The first is the relatively lively humor reigning in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a 40% decrease in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a large decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents from Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see figure 2).
About 44 per cent of respondents in the region were satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably higher than the 25% recorded in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% said they trusted their country’s Congress and 45 percent in their government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulence in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has stood during the global financial crisis is likely due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
Moreover, the existence of a stronger social safety net has helped protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only marginally increase in 2009 and has declined again this year, to 32 percent.)
However, mood varies considerably from country to country (see chart 4).
Brazil’s good economic returns and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general feeling of progress.
Such sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crime has increased.
For the second time since the polls began, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see figure 5).
About 31% say that, whether they or a close relative, they have been the victim of crime in the last year, a figure that has fallen since 38% last year and that is the lowest percentage registered since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in greater support for private companies and the market economy: about 71% of respondents in the region say that private companies are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only 56% (see figure 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow its country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62 percent of respondents in Venezuela think the same (and 80% support private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chavez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises the most leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
