An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new life forms on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that it is possible that there are life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That makes it a very peculiar thing, although it has little to be a kind of really 'alien' way of life," Paul C said. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report featured in Thursday’s online edition of the publication Science.
For a long time, there have been six major essential elements for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have found that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, may continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar from Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated great speculation on the Internet about the possibility of the report indicating the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "does show is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider indispensable to life may not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not done by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA’s astrobiology institute, who led the study, focused on the Lake Monkey because it has elevated levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so it speculated that a microbe exposed to both could substitute one for another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"Accordingly, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
"However, arsenic is different enough that it does not work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, to put it a little, it clumps the biochemical machinery," explains Anbar.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt to and used to grow.
The microbe grows best with phosphorus, but the fact of demonstrating that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that there may be naturally a way of life that uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example had never been found to prove that it works.
Arsenic was more common in early Earth eras, he said, so researchers speculated that the first life forms may have used it.
"It does suggest that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth in the past," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
