Thursday’s ruling confirms that the plan meets the demands of the U.S. bankruptcy code, so there are no other legal obstacles to MGM being relaunched under the founders of Spyglass Entertainment, Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the top executives of what will be a small studio.
Staff will be reduced from 400 to approximately 320.
In reality, MGM will not leave Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase closes a planned 500 million dollar credit instrument to finance the operations and productions of the new MGM.
The investment bank is currently syndicating credit, which on its own is contributing 75 million dollars, and is expected to be financed by mid-December.
The restructuring process of the study began in May 2009, when investment bank Moelis and Co. was hired to give advice on the management needed to sort their finances, while struggling to make interest payments for 300 million dollars a year.
In August, Director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron President and bankruptcy business recovery expert, known for his work on Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper’s attempts to resolve MGM’s financial tribulations and satisfy the study’s more than 140 creditors required much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, in late 2009 the parties agreed to put the company on sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders and none willing to pay the more than 2 billion dollars that creditors were looking for.
Before the spring of this year, he returned to the design table while the MGM team began working on a restructuring plan that, after months of debate and internal disagreements, was finally backed by creditors in late October.
