More moderate side of order maintenance is promoted in China
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the passage in a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing quietly orders with military authority.
He wanted the female members of Chengguan, the burly policemen of China’s urban order, feared and despised for their whimsical crackdowns and their inclination to violence, to communicate a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Firm!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "How are the pretty girls!"
Four girls who barely passed their teens with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants to get attention.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four elegant hats placed perfectly on top of the hair tied with blue and white striped bows.
"Personally, I think they have a normal appearance," said Mr. Tang, conscionably.
"The models are cute."
More than one government has tried to clear the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
Guangdong Province changed the grayish green color of uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force by intimidating glances: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a discolous snack cart, and watched it with a frown constantly for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women, specifically chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth, to its urban police.
The idea is to give the cough police a softer, feminine side.
Sadly, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s tiny respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, the critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portrays a different reality.
In January 2008, Hubei Province inspectors beat a passerby killed after using his cell phone to film them while they were disbanding a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and posted online, which described how to effectively whip criminals without bleeding them.
This year, a watermelon street vendor from Shanghai suffered brain damage after a scuffle with five officers.
A video game full of violence, available to download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
“Chengguan has left a scar on the government,” said China Daily, a national publication last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded "a really meticulous cleaning."
Skeptics say the current approach is a long way from this.
After the district requested through a notice eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News wondered if the women had royal duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a little bit of both.
