Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
The senator’s lawyers announced Wednesday that Justice Department prosecutors have exculpated Senator John Ensign from the criminal allegations that emerged from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to secure work through lobbying for the wife’s husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a potential Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign’s office said he was “surely happy” with the decision, which came after a full-year investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action from the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of his investigation and that he has no plan to bring charges against him on this issue."
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign may have colluded to violating a federal criminal lobby ban.
Interviews, email and other documents first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to get lucrative work through lobby, to achieve the silence of Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator’s affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer for an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find Mr. Hampton work and advocated for them after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an assistant to Ensign, he was excluded under the law of lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethic experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared at odds with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban," which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door statute," said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared cautious about accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks for its public integrity section, including last year’s decision to drop the prosecution of former Senator Ted Stevens, amid procedural misconduct charges.
Federal prosecutors “are clearly cowards,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, an advocacy group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them."
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s top lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and another call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to charge his client.
Ensign's defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Coggins declined to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave to prosecutors.
"I don't feel comfortable going into detail about my discussions with the Justice Department, I can only say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to change an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, which alleges that a US$96,000 payment from Ensign’s parents to the Hampton violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was nothing more than a gift.
NV Energy is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got a job through lobbying thanks to the help Ensign gave Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, reached out to Hampton and told him he was "slacking" the Interior Ministry over a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended a luncheon with Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and called the transportation secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When affairs news first appeared last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told reporters he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign spokesman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, he said the senator expected the ethics committee to quickly follow the Justice Department’s example and conclude its investigation.
"Sen. Ensign has a desire to continue his difficult work on behalf of the people of Nevada," he said.
Cheshire appeal to Twitter
There were half a dozen of them "chatting" in the ranks of the courtroom.
Minute by minute, they sent reports of the gruesome testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defense says, there were more than 140,000 Twitter messages about the process that addressed the rape and the children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the process widely followed by Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of a Cheshire family, Connecticut, is ready to reach an official end, with the judge’s imposition of the death penalty voted by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes’ lawyers have filed court briefs outlining the arguments for appeals that are likely to occupy the courts for years.
One of the most provocative claims that intense reports of the process, including the widespread use of Twitter by journalists of mass media, created "an atmosphere of circus", and such widespread and immediate saturation with exalting details made public passions exert an inappropriate influence on the jury.
The claim could force appeal judges to deal with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
“As I experienced during this process, I think there is a real danger that the inclusion of new technology in the courtroom is affecting the rights of the individual to have a fair process,” Thomas J said. Ullmann, senior defense attorney for Mr. Hayes.
Judge Jon C. Blue, of the State High Court, laconically rejected the lawsuits in a ruling last week, saying news media were "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury was led by passion.
But it probably won’t be the last word on the subject.
For decades, appeals courts have recognized that coverage of celebrated cases can raise questions about the fairness of a process.
In a landmark ruling in 1966, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, saying in his decision, in the Sheppard vs. Maxwell, that there was "an atmosphere of carnival in the process" due to the media.
The crime is believed to have been inspired by the TV show and the movie "The Fugitive."
Some lawyers said the appeals courts that examined Mr. Hayes’ conviction half a century later could be intrigued by the argument that new rules could be needed to control the form of communication from the courtrooms, something unimaginable in the time of Dr. Sheppard’s case.
"There is a general cause for concern about the impact of new media" on high-profile processes, John J said. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School, who studied the Connecticut death penalty and wrote a report saying it was arbitrarily imposed.
Professor Donohue said some appeals judges might be intrigued by the idea that limiting immediate communication from courtrooms could make trials fairer.
The Twitter issue is just one of many of the issues outlined by Hayes’ lawyers, which will likely be discussed for years, delaying an execution.
Defense attorneys also claim, for example, that Hayes could have been harmed when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential juries, showing them creepy photographs of the crime scene during jury selection.
Some jurors have said they were horrified by photographs of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17 and Michaela, 11.
Defense lawyers say they will also question the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge incorrectly removed a jury that had criticized prosecutors, and that he had incorrectly pushed for a verdict for his strange decision to order the jury to deliberate over a weekend.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But their arguments about the effect of intense coverage of the process may attract most interest.
They observed in a challenge to the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media continually fueled the fire of emotion about the case.
“The daily agglomeration of media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the courtroom,” the lawyers wrote, “was something never seen here in New Haven and maybe statewide.”
Your attention on Tweeter coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said the complaint about the fact that immediate news was more important than the reports delivered more slowly, were a Luddite view that would make the court’s policy on coverage control weak in future processes.
But some lawyers said the appeals courts were often drawn to arguments about the adaptation that was required in court due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pushing for that claim.
In their brief, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision, which overturns Dr. Sheppard’s conviction due to coverage of the process, and made it clear that they would demand that the new media would require new rules.
"This case," they wrote, "represents the Sheppard vs. Maxwell of the 21st century."
Can civility build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invectiveness and negativity, this week has triggered a bit of civility in Washington.
Is it a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders did not make any progress on the big issues that should be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone says, it was at least a courteous discussion about the differences of the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to earn partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit commission was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates the members.
That is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a probationary period, probing each other to identify signs of cooperativeness and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
Reason why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent assessments of it by participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate changes that have existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, spending, health care or social assistance, the two parties are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no doubt that things have changed with regard to how things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse party passions, which are then extinguished.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans can’t believe they’re in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefit for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s White House meeting, there is greater optimism for possible treatment of these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START nuclear disarmament pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112do. Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable, that a period of disagreement begins.
"After the things to be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to one of confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civility can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders have in the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they should try to keep their promises to cut state spending and overturn the new health care law.
Those party lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase of some taxes and the retirement age, and the cut in expenses.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken care of one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get close to that number.
The increased resistance is among the officials elected on the panel, suggesting that in fiscal matters there are, at least currently, few bases or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between White House and Congressional Republicans.
The first will happen next year in the form of party clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama about the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a standstill, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks they are losing will probably change course and seek commitment.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are currently greater than they were in the mid-1990’s, and there appears to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there were between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort from both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
A leaked U.S. document portrays Moscow as the paradise of corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a "kleptocracy" and leaves a portion of the bribes and protection money that it collects directly from the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service handle huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical authority” takes its part as money rises on the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted by WikiLeaks on its website Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and he blames it for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a clean-up since.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have consistently denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won several lawsuits for libel over such allegations.
In September, when on a Russian television channel he was asked about a documentary that suggested he was corrupt, he said: "It's crazy, a hoax, a nuisance."
According to polls, the Russians overwhelmingly believe their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, since they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of that it is the diplomats of a foreign country who do that.
“The direct links of the Moscow city government with criminality have led some to call it ‘dysfunctional,’ and to claim that the government functions more like a kleptocracy than a government,” the statement said.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term of the criminal world and the mafia that literally means ‘roof’ or protection’) that crosses the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor’s office, as well as all sectors of the Moscow city government bureaucracy.
"Analysts identify a three-tier structure in Moscow's criminal world."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The SFS, the MVD and the militia are on the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a void in some areas, because the city does not provide some services."
The report claims that the SFS raises money from larger companies, and that police target small businesses.
One source, the report said, “explained that Moscow’s business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) since they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law.”
"For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority."
The note notes that, while money collection is complete, protection can be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who don’t pay quickly find their businesses closed on one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports on men taking suitcases, probably filled with cash, inside the same Kremlin.
"In its fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust the bureaucrats," Georgy Satarov, director of Indem's Moscow think tank, said in a recent interview.
"But he's a part of this bureaucracy."
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia."
Without politics, without an opposition, without a separation of power, he said, corruption is inevitable.
Nationally, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than US$300 billion per year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption conducted by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154th (countries are ranked from least to the most corrupt).
The revelation of the U.S. Embassy’s note, which did not occur until late at night Moscow time, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and even though Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow’s weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is fixing the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that the WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously over a revelation that U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this relates to our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policies in this country," he said.
"But to be honest with you, we don't suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it was done in such an immoral way."
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face past
In a concrete, weakly lit classroom, with stained and shelled walls, the director of the Anlong Veng High School remembered the man who had built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge Ta Mok.
"Everybody here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he cared about his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the Butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge fortress in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a mixed court in the United Nations and Cambodia issued the first conviction of a former member of the Khmer Rouge, sentencing former head of the well-known Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of those events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Khmer Rouge of Anlong Veng, complicating efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they can't do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Center, an independent organization investigating the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"This is generating divisions within families."
During the rule of the Khmer Rouge of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol-led government, the remains of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia’s border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last move that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led guerrilla warfare from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating in the 1996 Ieng Sary surrenders, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting the process.
Without the support of their benefactors, the older Khmer Rouge fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their weapons, the raso soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
“These people have made little profit after surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime."
"They were raised without any concept to do business."
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before dedicating himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Khmer Rouge was fine," he said.
"Ta Mok fed everyone."
"But now life is hard because we have to self-sufficiency."
The current Khmer Rouge court has also caused concerns here.
Earlier next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court’s mandate is to prosecute top leaders and those most responsible for crimes, but it has not said whether it will pursue cases in addition to those four.
This doesn’t help much to calm fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodian Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced labourers are thought to have died.
During a recent muggy afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden piles on a dirt road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows over the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Khmer Rouge.
She claimed that if the court called her, she would not show up.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," he said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, though experts and historians question him.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is just what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
"The reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to rejoin the broken pieces," he said.
"It is our obligation to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand."
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education’s high school history textbook, which contains less than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s link to the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court," he said.
"They have suspicions because they are not sure about the number of people the court will prosecute."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are starting to make an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a path with too many weeds and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a black soot rectangle covered by a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone salesman on the edge of the road, said he didn’t know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a strong spirit and many locals go there to pray to him," he said.
It was Nuom Sothea’s birthday, and later that day he decided to walk to the place of Pol Pot’s last break, where he would leave a bunch of ripe bananas hoping to have good luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its uranium reserve qualified for weaponry
In a surprise victory for President Obama’s campaign to protect nuclear material around the world, the Belarusian government announced Wednesday that it will give up its reserve of highly enriched uranium, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was revealed in a joint statement released after Foreign Minister Hillary Rodham Clinton met with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov on the sidelines of a security summit.
For years, the U.S. government had been trying to persuade Belarus to give up its highly enriched uranium and it looked like they had reached a point of no return last spring.
But U.S. officials told the Washington Post that a pair of operations classified with Belarus have been carried out in the past two months, to remove 84.82 kg of weapon-qualified uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
This prepared the ground for Wednesday’s agreement to remove the rest of the material, approximately 227 kg, according to an official, who spoke from anonymity due to the confidentiality of the issue.
The deal appeared to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
And apparently it was a good achievement to secure the invitation of the former Soviet republic to the next summit in 2012.
"I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit."
"This shows that this process is working," said Ken Luongo, president of the Society for Global Security, a group that promotes nuclear safety.
Clinton said the deal is "a very significant and important step" taken by Belarus.
In April 2009 Obama promised in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material worldwide in the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries did so under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of Obama’s Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko had declared that the nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have conserved highly enriched uranium (hundreds of kilograms of what is basically uranium qualified for weaponry) and low-enriched uranium," Lukashenko said at the time.
"This is our raw material ... we're not going to make dirty bombs, and we're not going to sell them to anyone."
"We use it for research purposes, that's all."
However, Belarus approached the United States a few months ago, indicating interest in reaching an agreement.
Officials said the first task of removing uranium from Belarus in October was particularly complicated, as the material had been slightly irradiated.
Officials said it was loaded on a special train that traveled more than 2,000 km to a Russian facility for storage and disposal.
According to officials, the second operation ended Monday and was made by plane.
The U.S. government spent 13 million dollars for the tasks, and most of the money was used to supply Belarus with the installation of low-enrichment uranium research, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew Bieniawski, an Energy Department official working on Global Threat Reduction, said "this was carefully coordinated and orchestrated to strengthen confidence" that led to the agreement signed by Clinton.
The James Martin Center for Nonproliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus possessed at least 40 kilograms of uranium qualified for armaments, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will try to remove its reserve by 2012, according to the joint statement.
