Sport and fraud of law
Tretas like those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not willingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly concocted by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behavior is unsportsmanlike and if, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with a few minutes to finish the match (which their team already had clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time when it comes to taking two fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
That way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned with two matches the coach of the team, José Mourinho, and with different economic amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that emerged in the case reported is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and that on past occasions it has fined its players for similar acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, if these actions commit fraud of law; for, in effect, they are actions respectful of sports regulations, but they seem to avoid their meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that the sporting spirit comprises is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is referred to with fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from taking advantage of the opposing team unfairly, which did not happen either.
Now, the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it did not accommodate what we normally characterize as a trap or fraud of law, because its violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely its action tried to be the most obvious to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage infringers gain in the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to verify that the opponent is not disadvantaged or profited in the same match, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it is not a useful strategy for the next match, because the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is an advantage in the long term, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated to the first of change, and also with this performance the players fulfill a penalty match and go to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension for accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it’s not so clear that it’s an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is a part to make strategic decisions that favor making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case that concerns us, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the punishment or fleeing it.
Although the border between ingenuity and fraud of law is diffuse, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the guideline was carried out to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical and aesthetic.
