EU changes rules for obtaining visa
Individuals must go to Visa Applicant Service centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and wait time.
From January 10, 2011 the procedure of processing a visa will change at the U.S. Embassy and consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants will need to go to Visa Applicant Service (ASC) centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the applicant’s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to make the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a one-time payment that will cover all three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visa cases with petition (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for visas of merchants and investors.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this less time than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for a visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of 26 dollars.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/noveletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
