One thing is clear, the 2018 edition of the FIFA competition will be held in Europe, traditional bastion of discipline (four candidates: England, Russia, Spain-Portugal and the Netherlands-Belgium).
The 2022 edition will be much more exotic, given that the International Federation hopes to conquer new territories (Qatar, Australia), after a premiere on the African continent in 2010, or continue with its implementation in the United States or in the Far East (Japan, South Korea).
The list of personalities who were part of the delegations (David Cameron, Prince William, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero, José Socrates, Bill Clinton, the emir of Qatar, the Belgian and Dutch heads of government, Zidane, Beckham, Cruyff) attests to the economic and political interests that are at stake in a World Cup.
Cross-frame transactions, therefore, may last until the last minute.
Otherwise, it is difficult to establish a hierarchy among candidates.
According to FIFA’s evaluation report, the English, Spanish-Portuguese (2018) and American (2022) nominations have better arguments than their competitors.
However, these considerations will not be too important for the 22 members of the executive committee when voting.
The Sunday Times, responsible for the revelations that led to the suspension for corruption of two members of the CE (Reynald Temarii and Amos Adamu), could have thus ruined the opportunities of their country, the birthplace of football, which only hosted the World Cup once, in 1966.
The BBC added firewood to the stake on Monday by releasing a documentary that has exposed three influential EC members, Ricardo Teixeira, Nicolas Leoz and Issa Hayatou.
Enough to dislike FIFA and embarrass English officials, who have jumped into intense lobbying in recent weeks with David Cameron at the head.
The Head of Government hopes to reissue the successful blow by his predecessor, Tony Blair, who had won the JJ.OO organization for London in 2005. 2012.
Will this intense activity be enough to recover England’s brightness to the EC?
It is not clear, since the Spanish-Portugal duo also have numerous strengths thanks to their stadiums, already ready, their experience (World Cup of 82 in Spain, JJ.OO in Barcelona in 1992, European Cup in 2004 in Portugal) and their football culture.
However, the bleak economic and financial prospects of both countries could bring down their ambitions.
The possible reprisals against the English and the doubts about the solvency of Spain and Portugal the only thing they manage is to give points to Russia, turned into an outsider of weight despite the gaps in his candidacy (stadiums, hotels, transport).
However, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin decided not to move to Zurich and has denounced an "unfair competence in the preparation of the vote", in a direct allusion to the accusations of the English press against the members of the EC.
"They're bringing out their dirty rags, trying to compromise them," Putin said.
By 2022, the United States, which has the experience of 1994, seems the most logical favorites.
The world’s leading economic powerhouse and home to FIFA’s main sponsors, the country seems to take advantage of Japan and South Korea, which have separately developed an excellent project.
However, these new nominations seem premature for two countries that have organized the championship together in 2002.
Another risk: the concession of the 2026 World Cup to China, fervently desired by FIFA, which would cause Asia to run out of possibilities for 2022.
Together with Qatar, which has presented its project based on futuristic stadiums, and Australia, FIFA would continue its expansion towards new horizons, but both countries present more risks than certainties.
Australia, like Japan and Korea, could also be harmed by the weakness of paid TV rights (depending on the time difference) by European countries, the backbone of the war for FIFA.
