Euro: ECB is forced to maintain its acquisitions of state letters
The last meeting of the Council of Governors of the European Central Bank (ECB) of the year should allow to specify the modalities of exit from the crisis or, at least, announce the interruption of a large number of unconventional monetary policy operations that should end at the end of the year.
Because of the European sovereign debt crisis, the Frankfurt issuing institute will certainly not be able to afford to be so peremptory if it does not want to risk aggravating a more than complicated situation today in the European bond markets.
The political cost would be equally high.
Yesterday, during a press conference, the French Finance Minister, Christine Lagarde, has supported the active role played by the ECB in favour of solving the debt crisis of European states.
He did not want to say if he considered that the central bank should do more, increasing for example its program of purchase of state obligations.
"I reserve my opinion for my fellow Europeans" ...
The day before, in Brussels, during his hearing before the Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs of the European Parliament, the president of the ECB, Jean-Claude Trichet, was no longer eloquent in terms of his intentions, indicating only that the program of purchase of State Letters in the secondary market "continued" and that "we will see what we decided" during the meeting on Thursday.
The only thing that is clear is that the ECB will keep its main invariable rate at 1%, the lowest level in its history since May 2009.
In practice, the acquisition of Treasury obligations by the ECB has doubled last week to close to 1.350 million euros.
In addition, according to the indiscreet market operators, yesterday it would have bought again Irish and Portuguese titles.
In total, the eurosystem’s central banks have acquired securities for an amount of 67,000 million euros since May 2010.
Among market operators, there is no doubt the least that purchases will follow (see page 29).
Economists also do not foresee any significant changes of course.
Although loan operations more than three months have already disappeared from the ECB’s arsenal, the ECB still makes unlimited liquidity allocations to beneficial conditions and with durations ranging from one week to three months.
Economists expect this device to continue today for a few months.
"I can't imagine you're going to significantly modify your program."
“If not, it would risk causing new tensions in the short term,” says Michael Schubert, an economist at the Commerzbank.
"It seems more likely that there will be a progressive exit announced during the first quarter of 2011," said Norbert Bräms, an economist in Sal.
Oppenheim.
With regard to interventions in the public debt market, "the ECB should maintain a volume of purchase of such obligations so that the market remains stable," adds Norbert Bräms.
Given the importance of European bank exposures to euro area sovereign debt markets, the issuing institute has no choice but to maintain its market presence.
"It must compensate at any price for the lack of investors in the market and act in such a way as to prevent a marked increase in returns paid by the most fragile states," said a major bond manager.
Because, if interest rates turn through the clouds, states will have even more trouble reducing their indebtedness, or even to stabilize it.
This is the price of protecting the euro.
In Italy, Berlusconi’s government weathers the storm
After Italy started the week in a disturbing way, the situation improved slightly yesterday with the ebb of the rates of 10-year obligations.
A recovery from precarious calm.
Upon the departure of a meeting with the Minister of Economy, the regional presidents have said that they heard Giulio Tremonti call the situation "indecipherable" and that an "unpredivisible" weekend was expected, statements subsequently denied by the interested party.
If anything, on Tuesday the gap with German long-term rates had reached the record figure of 210 basis points and the price of hedge contracts against the risk of bankruptcy (CRQ) had soared to 263 points, causing a certain stir in Rome.
At the Council of Ministers, Silvio Berlusconi commented that, in Spain, the difference with German rates was more than 400 basis points.
But his right arm, Gianni Letta, expressed "deep concern" about "market turbulence" and possible contagion from Ireland.
"The good news is that Italy, the third largest economy in the euro area, is not like Greece or Ireland."
“The bad news is that it’s like Portugal,” explains Irwin Stelzer, an economist at the Hudson Institute.
In fact, its problem is the lack of growth and the stagnation of income associated with it, which causes the State to run the risk of not being able to meet its financing needs.
The latest forecasts from Brussels have meant a jar of cold water for the government.
It is estimated that Italian growth will reach 1.1% in 2011 and 1.4% in 2012, while the budget being reviewed in the Senate is based on figures of 1.3% and 2%, respectively.
Under these conditions, according to the European Commission, the public deficit will represent 4.3% of GDP next year (up from 3.9% planned by the government) and 3.5% in 2012 (instead of 2.7%).
Hence the rumor that new budgetary provisions can be applied after the holidays, for an amount of 7,000 million euros.
"If necessary, new austerity measures must be adopted," Economic Affairs Commissioner Olli Rehn said.
Italy is currently supported by international institutions.
"The foundations of its economy are in order and its accounts in good condition, as we have been saying for a long time," said Arrigo Sadun, the Italian administrator at the International Monetary Fund responsible for Italy at the IMF.
"There is no immediate problem, either in the short or long term, because despite its considerable debt (119.2% of GDP in 2011, NDLR), the stabilization efforts requested from Italy are lower than those required of other countries," says Pier Carlo Padoan, chief economist at the OECD.
The problem of political instability remains.
On December 14, Silvio Berlusconi will face a no-confidence motion in the Chamber of Deputies, after which elections could be anticipated at the end of March.
In such a case, a period of reason would be opened for decision-making in the event of a serious crisis.
Europeans reflect on strengthening mechanisms to combat the crisis
