Snow and ice: 24 apartments on orange alert
Snowfall continues to cause circulation difficulties, especially in the secondary network in Brittany, and can affect various economic activities.
Currently, twenty-four departments are on orange alert due to the risk of snowfall and ice formation.
Eure, Eure-et-Loir, Deux-Sèvres and Vienne have joined the twenty departments that were already on orange alert, eighteen since Wednesday at noon and two, Dordogne and Gironde, joined the group at night.
According to Météo France, heavy snowfall affects the north of Gironde and Charentes, although it also snows slightly in Ile de France.
Layers of snow between 2 and 5 cm, punctually between 7 and 10 cm, are expected in the affected departments, and between 1 and 3 cm, or even up to 5 cm, in the Parisian region.
The affected departments are Charente, Charente-Maritime, Côtes d'Armor, Finistère, Gironde, Dordogne, Poitou and those of the regions of Lower Normandy, the Isle of France and Lemosin.
The snowfalls are strong enough to cause traffic difficulties and affect some economic activities, warns Météo France.
In the Côtes d'Armor, access to various departmental roads to heavy vehicles of more than 7.5 tons, including the Guingamp-Lannion and Saint-Brieuc-Loudéac axles, has been banned.
According to the gendarmes, circulation in the secondary network of Brittany is complicated, so they recommend that it not be driven except in case of need and the movement of certain TER vehicles during the day has been prohibited.
During Thursday, school transportation in Picardy has been banned.
No specific measure had been planned Wednesday night to limit the movement of heavy vehicles.
The prefecture "urges all drivers to drive with the greatest caution on the roads and to adapt their driving to the situation."
The Directorate-General for Civil Aviation (DGAC) asked airlines to cancel 25% of their flights at the Parisian airport in Roissy and 10% in Orly on Thursday because of the planned snowfall.
The DGAC recommends that air passengers contact their airline.
In Britain, Gatwick Airport, south London, and Edinburgh Airport in Scotland are closed until Thursday morning.
