Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks issue has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandaly in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation it belongs to) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khaddafi's sinisterly ridiculed profile has long been giving ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who engage in the occult not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little craving) the head of the secret services (if it could not be, I know, editor of the Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same one published by the Newsweek the previous week.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that the embassies, at least since the Second World War and since the Heads of States can call themselves or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for some limited exercises of representation, have been transformed into espionage centers.
Any viewer who watches research movies knows it perfectly, we just pretend we don’t know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "executioners".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
In the past, in Orwell’s time, he could conceive himself of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control each movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as is now the case, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer retain its own secrets endure?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secrecy, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means to remove all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put on the network any reserved information, since it would be like publishing it on a street poster.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, you can’t expect to hold confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a Head of State has moved by plane and has contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is a matter of science fiction and, therefore, novel, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in errands with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a cable telegraph (telephone).
Videotapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of the montage, while now the (digital) CDs only allow to advance or back from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the trips it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques take us back to horse carriages.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly being plotted in the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: France’s slops on its funding pledges
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked (called fast-tarf or early) financing pledges made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French slops have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing US$ 30,000 million between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged to contribute 7.2 billion euros in three years and France 1,260 million euros (i.e. 420 million a year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was appreciable and appreciated for what it really is worth: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2,200 million euros in 2010, which puts it on the right path towards fulfilling its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be “new and additional” to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Nowadays, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million are added in three years in fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, the costs of previous years and the total level of official development assistance are not referred to.
Specifically, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while seeking to meet its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between grants and loans.
Again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the calculation method.
Some, like France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that is going to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be computed for its commitments.
But France does not find such a reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making a 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); consult the EU document to see it for its own eyes.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France double abuses: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why did the other Member States go to continue donating when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not dumb...
The early financing chapter is a relatively short-term minutia in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be a grain of extra sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not.
Whatever it may be, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the remaining countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could move forward with discussions on gambling on long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of “additional character” or the method of counting loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive in relation to this issue as it is to others.
We therefore have hope for the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additional character” and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to advance negotiations.
Warning about pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old boy ingests 81 different chemicals on a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the old movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the food usually consumed by a child of about ten years in four meals and a snack a day.
These meals taken as a model, which respect the official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The stock of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances susceptible to acting as endocrine disruptors (EPs), according to studies from various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded on an individual basis, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to possibly carcinogenic and/or PE pollutants is of concern," the association said.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicide in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, included in food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna and even the loaf of bread or gum were seasoned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, salmon slice was the most "nutritious" with 34 chemical residues detected and even analysis of the plastic dish used to heat food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk generated by these “pollutant cocktails” to the consumer is “probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Alliance Europa Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the seriousness of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in the fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
